<font color=#FFFFFF>Author</font></td><td valign=top bgcolor=203450 class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/upopularmisconception.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Popular Misconception</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/26/02 1:41:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=805.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Some advice</span><hr size=1> There are several ways that a mystery can be solved. <br>
<br>
1) The villain gives himself away due to the overwhelming pressure of conscious - The Telltale Heat.<br>
<br>
2) The hero pieces together using observations and clues that he finds - Agatha Christie style.<br>
<br>
3) The hero can stumble upon the solution out of blind luck - Inspector Gadget<br>
<br>
4) The hero can infiltrate the enemy forces - James Bond<br>
<br>
Standard to all mysterys is a crime, a villain, a detective and the clues. <br>
<br>
Probably the best way, is to visualise your crime and conspiracy before the jedi arrive, look at the links and then sever them to find out where the clues would be. <br>
<br>
Maybe the Hutt like a particular food and the governor has a lot in the kitchens. Maybe there is someone on the inside who wants out and sees the Jedi as a way out. Maybe the Governor has a lot of texts on the Hutt or perhaps there is a room the Jedi can sense that they cannot see a door too.  <br>
<br>
There are endless possibilities and some of the examples are off the top of my head. As long as it makes sense and you keep the reader guessing then you should be okay. <br>
<br>
